Project Name : Student's Mental Health¶

Subtitle : Analysing and Exploring Demographic Variations in Student Mental Health¶

1a. Data Selection :¶

Columns Description :

  1. Timestamp - Date and time of the survey taken.
  2. Gender - Male or Female.
  3. Age - Present Age of the student.
  4. Year of Study- Which year the student is studying in?
  5. GPA - Student's current score.
  6. Depression Status - If the student is depressed? (Yes/No)
  7. Anxiety Status - Is the student going through anxiety? (Yes/No)
  8. Panic Attack - Is the student having panic attacks? (Yes/No)
  9. Treatment Status - Did the student visit any specialist for treatment? (Yes/No)

Predictions :

Using some Linear Regression methots and visualization like logistic, we plan to predict whether a student's mental health is likely to be "Good" or "Poor" based on gender, GPA, and course based on the conducted survey.

Besides, with additional columns like, stress level, Counselling sessions and updated GPA, will help us understand the current state of the Student's mental health post counselling sessions and whether these sessions helped them improve their academic scores.

1b. Stakeholder:¶

The Stakeholder for the mentioned project is "US Secretary of Education". This research will help the Secretary to understand how the Student's mental health is affected due to the increased academic structure and less of the social events and activities. Moreover, it will showcase how important it is for the education sector to organize the counselling sessions to improve the students health and academic scores.

1c. Objective of the Proposed Research¶

The research involves understanding and identifying student’s mental health, based on their Age, GPA scores, and the amount of stress they are going through because of their day-to-day activities. Figuring out the improvement based on their counselling sessions by implementing various qualitative and quantitative methods to the given data.¶
This study is based on the performance of the students in their academics, calculating their stress levels based on the three aspects – Depression, Panic attacks, and Anxiety and how this has affected their academics and concerns extended to family members and loved ones.¶
Above all, this will provide a brief summary and explanation of the Student's Mental health and their performances and the improvement in their stress levels after the counselling sessions based on the given dataset.¶

  mutate(Stress_level = case_when(
    Anxiety.Status == "Yes" & Depression.Status == "Yes" & Panic.Attack == "Yes" ~ "High",
    Anxiety.Status == "Yes" & Depression.Status == "Yes" | Panic.Attack == "Yes" & Anxiety.Status == "Yes" |
      Depression.Status == "Yes" & Panic.Attack == "Yes" ~ "Moderate",

6. Response Variable :¶

The response variable in our linear regression analysis are "Stress Level" and the "Updated GPA". Stress Level represents the present mental health of the student in the form of "High", "Medium" and "Low" data this is based on the Depression, Anxiety and Panic Attack status of the students in our dataset.

The formation of the Stress Level is as, suppose all of the three symptoms i.e. Depression, Anxiety and Panic Attack is present in the Student then it is identified as "High Stress", if either of the two symptoms is present then "Moderate Stress" and if student is going through any of the one symptom then it is represented as "Low Stress".

Additionally, a second survey was conducted post their Counselling sessions to understand the improvement in their academic scores. This column is based on the past scores and the couselling sessions.

We hypothesize that both of these columns (Stress Level and Updated GPA) is influenced by the below predictor data:

  1. Age
  2. Past GPA
  3. Depression Status and Range
  4. Anxiety Status and Range
  5. Panic Attack Status and Range
  6. Course

Our goal is to build a linear regression model to quantify these relationships and predict Stress Level and Improved GPA based on these predictors.

  5. Pair Pannels demonstrates the interconnection between Age, Depression, Anxiety, Panic Attacks, Counselling Range with their data in each of the levels and how they are paired with each other.

8. Linear Regression :¶

In this section we have modelled and quantified the relationships between one or more predictor variables and the outcome variables. It assists us in understanding how changes in the predictors are related to changes in the response variable.

  1. The link between the dependent variable Age and the independent variable Depression Range is specified in the first linear regression model. It denotes that we wish to predict Age using the Depression Range.

  2. Based on the "Counselling.Range" independent variable, the model attempts to predict the "Updated_GPA" the response.

  3. This model's purpose is to predict "Year of Study" dependent variable from "Depression.Range" the predictor variable. It means we're modeling "Year of Study" as the dependent variable and trying to figure out how "Depression.Range" effects or explains differences in "Year of Study."

  4. This model's goal is to predict "Age" dependent variable from "Anxiety.Status" the predictor variable.It means we're modeling "Age" as the dependent variable and trying to figure out how "Anxiety.Status" effects or explains changes in "Age."

  5. This model's objective is to forecast "Age" the response variable based on "Panic.Attack" independent variable. It means we're modeling "Age" as the dependent variable and trying to figure out how "Panic.Attack" effects or explains differences in "Age."

9. Multiple Linear Regression :¶

This Regression model is to predict "Updated_GPA" which is the dependent variable using two predictor variables: "GPA" and "Counselling.Range."It means we're modeling "Updated_GPA" as the dependent variable and trying to figure out how "GPA" and "Counselling.Range" influence or explain differences in "Updated_GPA."

  1. Plot 1: Linear Regression Line for GPA vs. Counselling Range
  • A scatterplot of the association between "GPA" (Grade Point Average) on the x-axis and "Counselling.Range" on the y-axis is shown in this plot.
  • The blue line represents the data-fitted linear regression line, illustrating the linear relationship between GPA and Counselling Range.
  • The individual data points are added to the plot using geom_point().
  • Geom_smooth() method adds the linear regression line but does not display the standard error around it.
  • labs() determines the plot's title and axis labels.
  • The plot is given a minimal theme by theme_minimal().
  1. Plot 2: Linear Regression Line for Updated GPA vs. Counselling Range
  • A scatterplot showing the association between "Counselling.Range" on the x-axis and "Updated_GPA" (Updated Grade Point Average) on the y-axis is shown in this plot.
  • The red line depicts the data-fitted linear regression line, illustrating the linear relationship between Counselling Range and Updated GPA.
  • The individual data points are added to the plot using geom_point().
  • geom_smooth()adds the linear regression line but does not display the standard error surrounding it.
  • labs() determines the plot's title and axis labels.
  • The plot is given a minimal theme by theme_minimal().

These plots allow you to evaluate how well the data points correspond with the linear regression lines and display and assess the linear correlations between distinct pairs of variables (GPA vs. Counselling Range and Counselling Range vs. Updated GPA). The regression lines reveal the degree and direction of the correlations between these variables.

10. Report :¶

The Student Mental Health project aims to study and analyse the Students current academic situation and predict their Stress levels based on their Age, Depression Status, Anxiety Status and Panic Attack Status. Additionally, how ouselling sessions helped the students to improve their academic scores.

Data Gathering: Surveys and questionnaires were handed to students on campus/universities to collect data. Stress levels, anxiety, depression, academic pressures, and access to mental health resources were among the issues covered in the surveys.

Data Preparation: Preprocessing of collected data included data cleansing, addressing missing responses, and encoding categorical variables. This made certain that the dataset was ready for the analysis. Since the data was collected by a survey, there wasn't any duplicacy in the data.

Data Exploration EDA (exploratory data analysis) :

To acquire more insight into the mental health state of Students, exploratory data analysis was performed. Visualizations such as pie chart, bar graph, Density Graph, histograms, scatter plots, correlation, Simple and Multiple regression were utilized to identify patterns and correlations between the variables.

Data Visualization

We have created multiple distinct graphs to get deeper insights and graphical representation of the data and their values where -

  1. Pie chart represents the Gender Distribution.
  2. Density Plot shows the Depression Range.
  3. Histogram displays the Age distribution.
  4. Bar Graph illustrates the most enrolled Courses.

Data Correlation

This gave the glimpse of the relationship between two quantitative variables by using various techniques and identified the correlation amongst them. And the relation demonstration is performed in the form of various different plots i.e. Box Plot which illustrates the relation between the Anxiety Range and Panic Attack Range.

Scatter Line Plot demonstrates the correlation with the Counselling Session range and the Updated GPA.

3D Scatter Plot gives the glimpse of the correlation between three variables Depression, Anxiety and Panic attack.

Heatmap displays the graphical representation with calculated values for Depression, Anxiety and Panic Attacks and defines the relationship between these variables.

Pair Pannels demonstrates the interconnection between Age, Depression, Anxiety, Panic Attacks, Counselling Range with their data in each of the levels and how they are paired with each other.

Regression Models

1. Simple Linear Regression

we have modelled and quantified the relationships between one or more independent variables and the dependent variables. It assists us in understanding how changes in the predictors are related to changes in the response variable.

The independent variables used for this model are - Depression Range, Counselling Range, Anxiety Range, Panic Attack Range. The dependent variables are - Stress level and Age.

2. Multiple Linear Regression

This Regression model is to predict "Updated_GPA" which is the dependent variable using two independent variables: "GPA" and "Counselling.Range."

It means we're modeling "Updated_GPA" as the dependent variable and trying to figure out how "GPA" and "Counselling.Range" influence or explain differences in "Updated_GPA."

Plots

  1. Box Plot for Stress level vs Age which depicts that the stress level is high between the range of 19 - 25 Age category students.

  2. Bar graph represents the Genderwise Depression Range and it is clearly seen that the depression range is beyond 5 in both Male and Female.

Recommendation :

Based on our research and the analysis that has been conduted, It is plain to observe that the Highest level of stress is seen in Undergrads students and it is also clearly visible that there have been a drastic progress in their academic scores post Counselling sessions.

We would strongly like to recommend below points to our stakeholder to be considered.

  • The State should conduct social awareness camps regarding mental Health and provide free Counselling sessions which will be anonymous.
  • The State should also provide assistance to the Schools and Universities to have a health care center which will help and accomodate Counselling Sessions every quarter.
